abstract: Celebrate Pi Day (3.14.15) with three pi-related challenges by Keith Devlin, Gary Antonick and Kalid Azad.
snippet: Celebrate Pi Day (3.14.15) with three pi-related challenges by Keith Devlin, Gary Antonick and Kalid Azad.
lead_paragraph: Happy π Day! Saturday’s 3.14.15 comes around only every hundred years, so let’s have some fun acknowledging the most famous ratio in mathematics. (In case you missed it, check out yesterday’s crossword by Tom McCoy, a sophomore linguistics major at Yale.)

abstract: The nation’s biggest banks pass the Fed’s latest stress tests. | AbbVie goes on the defensive after deal for cancer drug maker. | Bidders show interest in the government’s third Bitcoin auction. | Nasdaq’s long climb back to 5,000.
snippet: The nation’s biggest banks pass the Fed’s latest stress tests. | AbbVie goes on the defensive after deal for cancer drug maker. | Bidders show interest in the government’s third Bitcoin auction. | Nasdaq’s long climb back to 5,000.
lead_paragraph: BIG BANKS PASS STRESS TESTS | All 31 of the nation’s biggest banks appear to have enough financial strength to survive a severe downturn in the United States economy, according to the results of the so-called stress tests that the Federal Reserve released on Thursday. But some banks fared better than others, DealBook’s Peter Eavis writes.
headline_main: Morning Agenda: Big Banks Pass Stress Tests

abstract: In one resort town after another, the Republican presidential hopefuls are making their case to exclusive gatherings of donors whose wealth was unleashed by the Supreme Court’s Citizens United decision.
snippet: In one resort town after another, the Republican presidential hopefuls are making their case to exclusive gatherings of donors whose wealth was unleashed by the Supreme Court’s Citizens United decision.
lead_paragraph: PALM BEACH, Fla. — Instead of the corn dogs and pork chops on a stick ritually served up on the hustings of Iowa, the latest stop on the donor trail featured meals of diver scallops and chocolate mousse. The setting was the Breakers, a sprawling Italian Renaissance-inspired hotel here, where the cheapest available rooms fetched $800 a night. And for the half-dozen Republican presidential candidates invited to the annual winter meeting this weekend of the Club for Growth, an influential bloc of deep-pocketed conservatives, the prize was not votes. It was money.

abstract: Through sickness and in health, Scrabble served as the backdrop for the relationship of Matthew Danzig and Elisabeth Hall.
snippet: Through sickness and in health, Scrabble served as the backdrop for the relationship of Matthew Danzig and Elisabeth Hall.
lead_paragraph: In February 2011, Matthew Danzig defeated Elisabeth Hall in their first game of Scrabble and immediately regretted it. It was during their first meeting, and even though OkCupid’s little robots predicted they were a 99 percent match, he wasn’t sure revealing his competitive side was putting his best foot forward.
headline_main: Couple Played the Tiles They Were Dealt

abstract: Roomy Khan made a pile of money trading on inside information. Then she cooperated with the F.B.I. Where does she go from here?
snippet: Roomy Khan made a pile of money trading on inside information. Then she cooperated with the F.B.I. Where does she go from here?
lead_paragraph: One day in the middle of 2008, Sakhawat Khan, a Silicon Valley chip engineer, walked into a small house near the back of his two-acre property that his wife, Roomy, a stock trader, used as a home office. Roomy and Sakhawat met when they were electrical-engineering students at Columbia University. After graduating, Sakhawat started inventing, eventually gathering some 30 semiconductor patents to his name. Roomy, who was more outgoing in social situations and more restless in her appetite for risk, was drawn to Wall Street and joined Galleon Group, a New York hedge fund run by the charismatic, bullish trader Raj Rajaratnam. In 1999, she struck out on her own to trade technology stocks. She thrived. Riding the Internet boom, she said, she had amassed a paper fortune of $50 million.

snippet: The company, seeking to reinvigorate its brand after some setbacks, plans to enhance the benefits of its popular gold card, but also raise the fees.
lead_paragraph: American Express, bruised by the recent loss of two major partnerships and an important court case, is seeking to reinvigorate its brand by sweetening the rewards on one of its most popular lines of cards.

abstract: David Hare’s play, which has transferred from London in a production directed by Stephen Daldry, finds two former lovers reuniting.
snippet: David Hare’s play, which has transferred from London in a production directed by Stephen Daldry, finds two former lovers reuniting.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — After Bill Nighy saw David Hare’s play “Skylight” in 1995, he telephoned the playwright to tell him he had never had a better night in the theater. “I was exhilarated,” Mr. Nighy recalled. “It was everything I loved and admired, and I picked up the phone and said, ‘David! I’ve just seen “Skylark.’ ”

abstract: The Republican resistance in Congress surrendered to President Obama’s call to protect an open Internet, with rules likely to be approved by regulators on Thursday.
snippet: The Republican resistance in Congress surrendered to President Obama’s call to protect an open Internet, with rules likely to be approved by regulators on Thursday.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senior Republicans conceded on Tuesday that the grueling fight with President Obama over the regulation of Internet service appears over, with the president and an army of Internet activists victorious.
